04516nam a22005775i 9780822392835DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20112012ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223928357 a10.1515/97808223928352doi  a(DE-B1597)553290  a(OCoLC)1172787470  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aML3534 7aMUS0190002bisacsh04a781.660900aMetal Rules the Globe :bHeavy Metal Music around the World /cJeremy Wallach, Harris M. Berger, Paul D. Greene. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2011] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (392 p.) :b14 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAffective Overdrive, Scene Dynamics, and Identity in the Global Metal Scene -- tThe Globalization of Metal -- t"A Dream Return to Tang Dynasty" -- tUnleashed in the East -- tElectronic and Affective Overdrive -- tOtherwise National -- tThe Marketing of Anglo-Identity in the North American Hatecore Metal Industry -- tMusical Style, Ideology, and Mythology in Norwegian Black Metal -- t"You Are from Israel and That Is Enough to Hate You Forever" -- tArenas of the Imagination -- tThunder in the Far East -- tMetal in a Micro Island State -- tNoisy Crossroads -- tNako -- tAFTERWORD -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tWORKS CITED -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the past three decades, heavy metal music has gone global, becoming a potent source of meaning and identity for fans around the world. In Metal Rules the Globe, ethnographers and some of the foremost authorities in the burgeoning field of metal studies analyze this dramatic expansion of heavy metal music and culture. They take readers inside metal scenes in Brazil, Canada, China, Easter Island, Indonesia, Israel, Japan, Malaysia, Malta, Nepal, Norway, Singapore, Slovenia, and the United States, describing how the sounds of heavy metal and the meanings that metalheads attribute to them vary across cultures. The contributors explore the dynamics of masculinity, class, race, and ethnicity in metal scenes; the place of metal in the music industry; and the ways that disenfranchised youth use metal to negotiate modernity and social change. They reveal heavy metal fans as just as likely to criticize the consumerism, class divisiveness, and uneven development of globalization as they are to reject traditional cultural norms. Crucially, they never lose sight of the sense of community and sonic pleasure to be experienced in the distorted, pounding sounds of local metal scenes.Contributors. Idelber Avelar, Albert Bell, Dan Bendrups, Harris M. Berger, Paul D. Greene, Ross Hagen, Sharon Hochhauser, Shuhei Hosokawa, Keith Kahn-Harris, Kei Kawano, Rajko Muršič,Steve Waksman, Jeremy Wallach, Robert Walser, Deena Weinstein, Cynthia P. Wong  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aHeavy metal (Music)xHistory and criticism. 0aMusic and globalization. 0aRacism in popular culture. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Heavy Metal.2bisacsh1 aBerger, Harris M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGreene, Paul D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWallach, Jeremy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822392835zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822392835423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822392835.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles